{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517098"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:50:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:50:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12757"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12757"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.05,0.08,0.19,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5204"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109724"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5204"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12757"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92121"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"176"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8828"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9756"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44290"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109724"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents with a four-day history of right hip pain. The pain came on suddenly while rising from a chair, with no history of trauma. He has never experienced similar hip pain before and now requires a walking aid. His medical history includes hypertension, diabetes and hypothyroidism. His regular medications include metformin, perindopril and thyroxine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has severe pain on passive movement of the right hip. Lower limb pulses are present bilaterally and neurological examination is normal. Radiographs show normal bone density with a displaced right femoral neck fracture. Laboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 135 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChloride 105 mmol/L (100-109)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate 25 mmol/L (22-32)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcium 2.75 mmol/L (2.10-2.55)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 133 \u00b5mol/L (50-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 95 g/L (135-175)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean cell volume 90 fL (80-98)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll laboratory values were normal one year ago. He is up-to-date on routine health screening.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations would be most appropriate to determine the underlying diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum protein electrophoresis","Technetium-99m bone scan","Parathyroid hormone-related protein","Parathyroid hormone","Dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a pathological fracture and laboratory findings suggestive of multiple myeloma, including hypercalcaemia, normocytic anaemia, and renal impairment. These features, known as CRAB (hypercalcaemia, renal failure, anaemia, and bone lesions), are characteristic of multiple myeloma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum protein electrophoresis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation as it can detect and quantify the presence of monoclonal proteins (paraproteins) produced by abnormal plasma cells. This test is highly sensitive for multiple myeloma and is the recommended screening test when the condition is suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETechnetium-99m bone scan\u003C/strong\u003E would be of limited value in this case. While it can detect areas of increased osteoblastic activity, multiple myeloma primarily causes lytic lesions which may not be detected on bone scan. A skeletal survey by CT or MRI (STIR) would be more appropriate for detecting myeloma bone disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParathyroid hormone-related protein\u003C/strong\u003E is typically elevated in malignancy-associated hypercalcaemia from solid tumours. While this could explain the hypercalcaemia, it would not account for the anaemia and renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParathyroid hormone\u003C/strong\u003E measurement would be appropriate if primary hyperparathyroidism was suspected. However, this would not explain the combination of anaemia and renal impairment, making it less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDual-energy X-ray absorptiometry\u003C/strong\u003E measures bone mineral density and is useful in diagnosing osteoporosis. However, the radiographs already show normal bone density, and DEXA would not detect focal lytic lesions characteristic of multiple myeloma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple myeloma commonly presents with hypercalcaemia, renal dysfunction, anaemia, and pathological fractures (CRAB features).","Serum protein electrophoresis is the initial screening test of choice for suspected multiple myeloma."],"references":["Malard F, Neri P, Bahlis NJ, Terpos E, Moukalled N, Hungria VTM, et al. Multiple myeloma. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2024 Jun 27;10(1):1\u201321.","Palumbo A, Anderson K. Multiple myeloma. N Engl J Med. 2011 Mar 17;364(11):1046-60. [PubMed]"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92121"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12757"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92121"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-25T18:31:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-25T18:31:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5204"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109724"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpret